I believe the answer is highly likely to be no. Both sides have announced certain preconditions that seem to be mutually exclusive: Iran wants the initiative to come from the US by lifting all economic sanctions, and the latter calls for an immediate stop to uranium enrichment in Iran to lift the sanctions. Moreover, Iran currently experiences high tensions on its northern borders with Azerbaijan where it has multimillion Azeri population. Iran has deployed heavy military arsenal and warned that it would not tolerate any attack on its sovereignty. Making compromises in other international directions would undermine Raisi's domestic reputation as a hardline actor. The Biden administration has already mentioned more than once that they are ready to discuss JCPOA revival, but they have not received any substantive offers. They see their announcement of rejoining JCPOA as a main compromise to Iran. Taking into account the withdrawal from Afghanistan, the administration is unlikely to demonstrate much more detached position in this part of the Middle East. Even some European partners seem to be more flexible on this question, but their position had little effect on the US position. If you add to this equation Israel's hardened posture, everything becomes more puzzled. Recent developments in the US-Russia relations in terms of closing the Russian representation in NATO also demonstrates that the US currently is constrained in its eastern policies. I think when two states come from directly opposite political blocks with some turbulent political background, it is vital to lay a basis to recover the trust and willingness to understand each other's concerns. Once there is progress on this matter, anything else becomes technicality.

Regardless of the interest level of the Biden administration to rejoin JCPOA, Iran's continued enrichment of uranium, hardline statements from Iran's leadership, and the repeated delays in talks make it very unlikely that the U.S. even be able to rejoin the JCPOA. Not only has the Iranian Foreign Minister, Hossein Amir-Abdollahian, indicated JCPOA would not be a possibility during his tenure, the JCPOA is not a priority issue for the new president, Ebrahim Raisi. (https://foreignpolicy.com/2021/10/07/iran-deal-talks-jcpoa-vienna-nuclear-negotiations-raisi/#) Also, as Iran continues to enrich uranium, the JCPOA is simply loosing relevance as Iran moves past the terms set by the JCPOA. Iran is also reluctant to trust the U.S. again and is skeptical that the U.S. will lift the current sanctions. (https://foreignpolicy.com/2021/09/22/separate-nuclear-iran-deal-jcpoa-regional-security-saudi-arabia-uae/) Both parties have to want and need the deal. Iran does not want it and seems to be able to manage the effects from the economic sanctions to the point where it doesn't need the deal - especially within the next 2 1/2 months.

Iran Nukes the Case for a Biden Deal - The Wall Street Journal https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-nuclear-deal-biden-blinken-jcpoa-ebrahim-raisi-khamenei-11628539180 Tue, 10 Aug 2021 12:52:00 GMT > But Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei has no intention of ending up like Mikhail Gorbachev. By ruthlessly engineering the election of a hard-liner’s hard-liner to the presidency, Mr. Khamenei has slammed the door on normalization and nailed it shut. > That’s only one of the problems afflicting the JCPOA. Instead of welcoming the Biden administration’s eagerness to return to President Obama’s Iran policy, Tehran has turned up its nose at American attempts to chart a course back to mutual compliance with the terms of the deal. The ease with which President Trump was able to dump the JCPOA, and the inability of outraged Europeans to contest his imposition of unilateral sanctions, created a healthy skepticism in Iran about the deal’s value. Tehran has realized that an executive agreement like the JCPOA has no legal force in the U.S. It is not simply that a future president could follow Mr. Trump’s footsteps and reject the nuclear deal. President Biden could sign the JCPOA one week and reimpose American sanctions on whatever grounds he chose the next, and Iran would have no recourse. > Rather than seeing American withdrawals from Afghanistan and Iraq as friendly gestures meriting a constructive response, the mullahs appear to have interpreted them as a sign that the Biden administration can be safely defied. Likely believing the White House is bent on Middle East withdrawal, no matter the cost, Tehran seems to have decided to double down on its confrontational approach to capitalize on perceived U.S. weakness. > A deepening confrontation with a radicalizing Iran is not what the Biden administration expected from its Middle East policy, but that is the reality with which it must cope. Attempting to placate Tehran through patience and restraint will likely only stoke the regime’s ambitions. The smell of blood in the water rarely inspires feelings of moderation and restraint among sharks.

The complexity of the US officially rejoining the JCPOA may be significant than I initially considered. I had previously focused on the renegotiation between the US, Iran, and the four other signatories. The contours of the rejoining the JCPOA matter. Congressional review appears like it will add 30-days.

Thank you for your thoughtful response, @dowser. I agree with your premise that both sides continue to have incentives to come to agreement. My point was that Iran and Iranian leaders tend to have a much longer time horizon than do Western democracies with comparatively frequent and meaningful elections. The clerical Iranian leaders likely see no dissonance between this shocking breach of international law (in my earlier post about Iranian intelligence seeking to kidnap an American on U.S. soil) and their continued, slow, painful negotiations in Geneva. The current grouping of states seeking to subvert the post-World War II rules-based International Order (China, Russia, North Korea, Iran) all engage in these so-called “salami-slicing” tactics, to which I did not give adequate weight. I was previously well above the crowd (80%) and this event caused me to reevaluate my excessive optimism for a resolution within our question’s timeframe. I agree they very well may come to agreement, but I am just not as optimistic as I was that it would be in time for a “yes” on our question.

The Islamic Republic of Iran is undergoing presidential elections in mid-June 2021, which will likely see a hardliner, most likely the head of the judiciary, win the vote, within a relatively low turnout caused by disillusionment and frustration also given the exclusion of several moderate candidates. This will hamper the room for maneuver of ongoing negotiations on the nuclear issue, which had a first meeting in Vienna last April, here significant discrepancy between US willingness to start lifting some sanctions not related to the JCPOA and Tehran request for all sanctions' lift. The US demands include a revision of the agreement including a regional dimension focused on Iran's support of non state armed groups in Yemen, Syria, Lebanon, Gaza, Iraq and elsewhere in the region. All considered, negotiations are complex and expected to last several months, and the outcome of presidential elections will play a big role. Another factor to take into consideration will be the role of regional actors, given recent rapprochement, at least formally, between Saudi Arabia and Iran, which might facilitate talks to proceed.

This is a complex foreign policy problem for the Biden Administration, made more difficult by Israel. The real questions here is how committed is Iran to the agreement and do they really have the ability/compacity to refine enough uranium for a nuclear bomb if they want to? While Iran has a highly educated society and capable scientists, do the they have the resources and/or the real desire to have a nuclear bomb? For example, despite being an oil rich country, energy prices in Iran are extremely high in comparison to other countries in the region. This could make an argument for and against domestic nuclear energy. On one hand the capital investment required to build a domestic nuclear reactor is in the billions (just look at the current nuclear power plant being built in Georgia, which is being delayed and at least a billion over budget). On the other hand, once up and running, domestic nuclear energy is fairly cheap. Bottom line, is domestic nuclear energy really the best course for Iran or do they really desire to have at least the ability to build a nuclear bomb? It would seem to be the latter. The US seems likely to rejoin the JCPOA because the US lacks a more efficient incentive structure to curb Iranian enrichment programs even with the threat or use of military force and President Biden has consistently stated he would rejoin the deal with Iran in some fashion. Thus, JCPOA remains the most convenient and effective way to bargain with Iran. (see first and second linked sources below). The main reason a rejoining of the deal is not assured is that "hawks" in Iran, and the US (and Israel) seem to be opposed to any deal with one another. As the Iranian government is largely unchanged since the original deal and the new US administration is committed to a deal in some fashion the "hawks" seem unlikely to sway the more moderate governing coalitions in both Iran and the US. Biden seems highly incentivized to make a deal happen before Iranian or Israeli elections. (see third linked source below). Very high likelihood of a deal in some fashion that is branded as under the auspices of the JPCOA in the next 11 months.
